Title: Alice Pheland and B. F. Enyeart pose in front of the Burbank City Schools' Tournament of Roses parade float framework, Pasadena vicinity, about 1936
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: L to R. Alice Phelan B. J. Enyear [sic]|~|Handwritten text from negative sleeve: 3183 - L to R. Alice Phelan Art supervisor and B. F. Enyeart, Supt of Burbank schools. supervise Rose float for Burbank. 1-10-36 [date stamp:] 1936
Description.note: A different photograph of the same Burbank parade float appears with the title, "Somebody Stole Burbank Rose Float Money--but Job Goes On!," and is captioned, "Theft of funds intended for Burbank School's entry in the Rose Tournament Parade at Pasadena, from a school safe Monday night, will not prevent construction of the Burbank entry, it was announced yesterday. The loss totaled $100. Some of the fund already had been spent and part of it was kept elsewhere. School officials, however, will replace the loss. The theme of the float will be "Chivalry." Jackie Searl, juvenile actor, who attends Burbank High School, will ride his own horse ahead of the float. Shown above, working on entry, is B. F. Enyeart, superintendent of schools, at extreme left., and school board members who volunteered to lend a hand to rush construction of the colorful creation. Times photo," Los Angeles Times, 27 Dec. 1935: 6|~|Text from accompanying note card in negative sleeve (Item Ark: 21198/zz002h823d ): ENYEARST [sic]. BUEL F. SEPT 16 34 BURBANK: SCHOOLS: SUPT. High school principal is named by Bd. of Educ. to fill position vacated by Curtis E. Warren, supt. of schools. (Burbank) 1-20-1|~|At center, from left to right, Alice Phelan and B. F. Enyeart, Burbank Schools Superintendent, pose in front of the framework for the Burbank City Schools' float entry into the Tournament of Roses. They both stand in profile, facing left, but turn their heads towards camera. Alice Phelan holds onto the framework behind her as she casts her gaze downward. The incomplete float stands in partial view behind them. Its design appears to emulate tracery and stained glass elements seen in Gothic architecture.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.

Title: Wreckage of Lieutenant Browne Clement's crashed Army plane lies in a grain field, Monterey Park, 1936
Description.caption: Handwritten text from negative sleeve: 3321 - Army plane crash at Monterey Park. Plane crash cra[?]e: de[?]lict back one a[?]ter. 4-4-36 [date stamp:] APR 14 1936
Description.note: A grain field in Monterey Park stretches across the foreground and back through the image. In the near distance at center, the wreckage of Lieutenant Browne Clement's aircraft lies crumpled on the ground. Along part of the plane, it reads, "52." The tail of the plane sits hidden behind a group of several investigators, who stand in a cluster to the right of the aircraft. Beyond the wreckage site, the field extends into the distance and towards 2 low mountains that rise at far left and far right.|~|This photograph is related to the article, "Death Ends Honeymoon: CRASH KILLS ARMY FLYER Plane Propeller Comes Off, Wrecking Wing, and Ship Goes Into Spin," Los Angeles Times, 05 Apr. 1936: 1|~|A different photograph of the same plane crash appears with the caption, "Propeller Comes Off, Wrecking Airplane Wreckage of Lieut. Browne Clement's' army pursuit plane in grain field at Monterey Park with March Field mechanics disassembling it for return to airport. Propeller shown in foreground was retrieved from front yard 500 yards away. Times photo," Los Angeles Times, 05 Apr. 1936: 2

Description.caption: Handwritten text from negative sleeve: 3321 - Army plane crash at Monterey Park. Plane crash cra[?]e: de[?]lict back one a[?]ter. 4-4-36 [date stamp:] APR 14 1936
Description.note: This photograph is related to the article, "Death Ends Honeymoon: CRASH KILLS ARMY FLYER Plane Propeller Comes Off, Wrecking Wing, and Ship Goes Into Spin," Los Angeles Times, 05 Apr. 1936: 1|~|A different photograph of the same plane crash appears with the caption, "Propeller Comes Off, Wrecking Airplane Wreckage of Lieut. Browne Clement's' army pursuit plane in grain field at Monterey Park with March Field mechanics disassembling it for return to airport. Propeller shown in foreground was retrieved from front yard 500 yards away. Times photo," Los Angeles Times, 05 Apr. 1936: 2|~|In the near distance at center, several members of the armed forces scour through the wreckage of Lieutenant Browne Clement's downed aircraft. The wreckage lies crumpled in a grain field and is viewed from the side. An identification mark on the tail of the plane at left reads, "52." Three men stand on the near side of the plane with their backs to the camera. Some debris from the crash lies between the camera and the nearest man. The outer layer of the plane is gone, allowing the camera a glimpse into the inner structure of plane's side. A few more men stand behind and to the left of the plane. The grain field stretches into the distance.

Description.caption: Handwritten text from negative sleeve: 14978 - wheelsmen + Sheriff Biscailuz 11-15-38 [date stamp:] NOV 23 1938 [credit stamp:] TIMES PHOTO BY ANDREW H. ARNOTT|~|Handwritten on negative: wheelmen 11-14-38 7 x [?...]
Description.note: A similar photograph of the same Wheelsmen’s organization meeting appears in a photospread titled, “Italy Pours 20,000 Emigrants From 15 Liners Into African Colony, Libya,” and captioned, “Old-Time Cyclists To Hold Annual Dinner Meet Bill Jenkins, left, Tracy Q. Description.caption: Typescript on negative: ARTHUR SANGER AND COLLECTION|~|Text from negative sleeve: SANGER, ARTHUR ARCHEOLOGIST [sic] 1928|~|Text from newspaper caption: SECRETS UNLOCKED OF PREHISTORIC RACE A. R. Sanger and Part of His New Collection [Los Angeles Times, 08 Apr. 1928: A2]

Sanger sits behind a small folding table set up on a porch. He faces slightly right and looks down towards the table as he holds a Native American instrument to his mouth. The table sits in front of him at center. A variety of Nicoleño relics and artifacts retrieved from a recent expedition to San Nicolas Island are on display. Bowls, pottery and some tools lie near the left edge of the table. Behind them, storage or display trays contain small tools and strings of beads. The wood siding of the building abuts the table at right. The rest of the building stretches across the background at left.

Title: Criminologist Frank Gompert inspects a pistol while Norris Stensland watches, [Los Angeles], about 1931
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: Norris Stensland - Frank B. Gompert
Description.note: Text from negative sleeve: STENSLAND, NORRIS DEP. SHERRIF [sic] 1931|~|Frank Gompert sits, off-center to the right, and hunches over a small table and microscope. He leans towards the left as he holds a pistol beneath the microscope. Below him and on the table sits a pile of bullets and casings, on or near their evidence sleeves. Behind and to the left of Frank Gompert, Norris Stensland sits and watches Frank Gompert handle the small firearm. At left, a typewriter and another pistol sit on the desk next to Norris Stensland. The rest of the laboratory occupies the background.

Title: Norris Stensland, Joe Taylor, Blayney Matthews and William Bright pose with suspects arrested for the kidnapping of John and Elaine Jeske, Los Angeles, [1934]
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: STENSLAND, NORRIS DEP. SHERRIF [sic] 1931|~|Handwritten on negative: standing l to r - Norris Stensland Joe Taylor, James Britton, Blainey [sic] Mathews [sic], Wm Bright seated l to r - Jerry Lamoreaux C R. Russell
Description.note: This photograph is possibly related to the article, "KIDNAPGANG IS CAPTURED: Chaney Widow's Gem Sought Four Held as Abductors of Chauffeur and Bride, Captives Twelve Days Tribute Extorted During Long Hours of Torture; Two Others Hunted," Los Angeles Times, 28 Jul. 1934: 1|~|In the front row, from left to right, Jerry Lamoreaux and Cecil R. Russell sit slumped in chairs upon their arrest on suspicion of kidnapping. Both cross their arms in front of them and either close their eyes or cast them downward. Behind them, from left to right, Norris Stensland, Joe Taylor, Floyd C. Britton, Blayney Matthews and William Bright stand in a row behind them. All but Floyd C. Britton are police. Floyd C. Britton is also arrested on suspicion of kidnapping.
